Exercise Report: Commute Time & Transportation

Author

Liang Lai, Joe Dainis

1 Summary

We analyzed five variables (Height, Weight, Gender, Time, and Transportation), created exploratory figures, and fit a linear regression model with Height as the outcome and Time and Transportation as predictors.

2 Introduction

2.1 Description of data and data source

Two additional variables were added to the original dataset. The variable Time measures the average one-way commute time from home to school in minutes and is numeric. The variable Transportation is categorical and indicates the primary mode of transportation used for commuting (walk, bike, car, or bus).

3 Methods

3.1 Data cleaning

In data cleaning process, we addressed obvious data entry issues (e.g., non-numeric height entries such as âsixtyâ and implausible values), converted variables to appropriate types, and removed observations with missing or clearly invalid values (e.g., missing weight or extreme outliers). The newly added categorical variable Transportation was explicitly treated as a factor with valid levels (walk/bike/car/bus).

3.2 Statistical analysis

We first conducted exploratory data analysis using figures, including a boxplot of Height by Transportation and a scatterplot of Weight versus Time, to assess distributions and potential relationships. We then fit a simple linear regression model with Height as the outcome and the two newly added variables (Time and Transportation) as predictors.
